docs/spec-build/epics/01-claude-impl-cli-skill/artifacts/story-01/005-verifier-codex54-xhigh.jsonl:11:{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_5","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"nl -ba docs/spec-build/epics/01-claude-impl-cli-skill/stories/01-run-setup-and-environment-resolution.md | sed -n '1,260p'\"","aggregated_output":"     1\t# Story 1: Run Setup and Environment Resolution\n     2\t\n     3\t### Summary\n     4\t<!-- Jira: Summary field -->\n     5\tDiscover story order, verification gates, and the active provider/model defaults so the orchestrator can start the run with a validated configuration.\n     6\t\n     7\t### Description\n     8\t<!-- Jira: Description field -->\n     9\t\n    10\t**User Profile**\n    11\t\n    12\t- **Primary User:** A Claude Code orchestration agent operating on behalf of a senior engineer or tech lead\n    13\t- **Context:** Running a completed spec pack through a disciplined implementation workflow without relying on conversation memory or ad hoc orchestration\n    14\t- **Mental Model:** \"I load a finished spec pack, confirm the environment and options, launch the right workflow through the CLI, and supervise implementation and verification until the epic is complete.\"\n    15\t- **Key Constraint:** Claude Code is always available. GPT model lanes depend on whether Codex CLI or Copilot CLI is available in the local environment.\n    16\t\n    17\t**Objective**\n    18\t\n    19\tComplete the remaining setup work after Story 0 by reading all story files, discovering story and epic verification gates, resolving available provider lanes, applying deterministic role defaults, and recording the resolved run configuration in the durable log.\n    20\t\n    21\t**In Scope**\n    22\t\n    23\t- Full story inventory and recorded story order\n    24\t- Verification-gate discovery and ambiguity handling\n    25\t- Provider availability checks\n    26\t- Role-specific model/harness defaults and degraded fallback behavior\n    27\t- Recording the resolved run configuration in `team-impl-log.md`\n    28\t\n    29\t**Out of Scope**\n    30\t\n    31\t- Prompt assembly\n    32\t- Public insert application\n    33\t- Story implementation or verification execution\n    34\t- Recovery after implementation has started\n    35\t\n    36\t**Dependencies**\n    37\t\n    38\t- Story 0 complete\n    39\t- Completed spec-pack artifacts present and recognized\n    40\t\n    41\t### Acceptance Criteria\n    42\t<!-- Jira: Acceptance Criteria field -->\n    43\t\n    44\t**AC-1.5:** The orchestrator reads all stories before starting implementation\n    45\t\n    46\t- **TC-1.5a: Full story inventory**\n    47\t  - Given: The epic folder contains multiple story files in `stories/`\n    48\t  - When: The skill performs run initialization\n    49\t  - Then: The orchestrator reads all stories and records the story order before Story 0 or Story 1 begins\n    50\t\n    51\t**AC-1.6:** The skill discovers and records the verification gates before implementation starts\n    52\t\n    53\t- **TC-1.6a: Gates discovered from project policy**\n    54\t  - Given: The project exposes verification commands through policy docs, scripts, or CI configuration\n    55\t  - When: The skill initializes the run\n    56\t  - Then: The orchestrator identifies the story and epic verification gates and records them in `team-impl-log.md`\n    57\t- **TC-1.6b: Gate policy ambiguous**\n    58\t  - Given: Project policy does not clearly identify the required verification gate\n    59\t  - When: The skill initializes the run\n    60\t  - Then: The orchestrator pauses to resolve the ambiguity before starting story implementation\n    61\t\n    62\t**AC-2.1:** Claude-only lanes are always available to the orchestrator\n    63\t\n    64\t- **TC-2.1a: Claude baseline**\n    65\t  - Given: The orchestrator is a Claude Code agent\n    66\t  - When: The skill resolves available lanes\n    67\t  - Then: Claude model lanes are always included in the available role options\n    68\t\n    69\t**AC-2.2:** Codex CLI is the preferred GPT provider when available\n    70\t\n    71\t- **TC-2.2a: Codex available**\n    72\t  - Given: Codex CLI is available\n    73\t  - When: The skill resolves provider options\n    74\t  - Then: GPT model defaults for eligible roles are assigned to Codex-backed lanes\n    75\t- **TC-2.2b: Codex unavailable, Copilot available**\n    76\t  - Given: Codex CLI is unavailable and Copilot CLI is available\n    77\t  - When: The skill resolves provider options\n    78\t  - Then: GPT model defaults for eligible roles are assigned to Copilot-backed lanes\n    79\t- **TC-2.2c: Neither Codex nor Copilot available**\n    80\t  - Given: Neither GPT-capable CLI is available\n    81\t  - When: The skill resolves provider options\n    82\t  - Then: The skill switches the run to Claude-only defaults and records that change explicitly\n    83\t\n    84\t**AC-2.3:** The skill defines role-specific available models, defaults, and fallback rules\n    85\t\n    86\t- **TC-2.3a: Story implementor defaults**\n    87\t  - Given: Codex CLI is available\n    88\t  - When: The skill resolves story implementor defaults\n    89\t  - Then: Story implementation defaults to Codex `gpt-5.4 high`\n    90\t- **TC-2.3b: Story implementor Claude fallback**\n    91\t  - Given: No GPT-capable CLI is available\n    92\t  - When: The skill resolves story implementor defaults\n    93\t  - Then: Story implementation defaults to Claude Sonnet high\n    94\t- **TC-2.3c: Story verifier defaults**\n    95\t  - Given: Codex CLI is available\n    96\t  - When: The skill resolves story verifier defaults\n    97\t  - Then: The default verifier pair is `gpt-5.4 extra high` plus Claude Sonnet high\n    98\t- **TC-2.3d: Story verifier Claude-only fallback**\n    99\t  - Given: No GPT-capable CLI is available\n   100\t  - When: The skill resolves story verifier defaults\n   101\t  - Then: The default verifier pair uses Claude-only verifier roles and records the weaker diversity condition\n   102\t- **TC-2.3e: Epic verification defaults**\n   103\t  - Given: GPT-capable lanes and Claude lanes are both available\n   104\t  - When: The skill resolves epic-level verification defaults\n   105\t  - Then: The epic verifier set and synthesizer default are selected from the defined allowed models and recorded in the run configuration\n   106\t\n   107\t**AC-2.4:** The orchestrator records resolved role defaults in `team-impl-log.md`\n   108\t\n   109\t- **TC-2.4a: Run configuration recorded**\n   110\t  - Given: Provider and model resolution completed\n   111\t  - When: The skill finishes environment setup\n   112\t  - Then: `team-impl-log.md` records available providers, active defaults, and any degraded fallback conditions for the run\n   113\t\n   114\t### Technical Design\n   115\t<!-- Jira: Technical Notes or sub-section of Description -->\n   116\t\n   117\t**Relevant Data Contracts**\n   118\t\n   119\t#### Role Model Matrix\n   120\t\n   121\t| Role | Primary Use | Default | Fallback | Session Shape |\n   122\t|------|-------------|---------|----------|---------------|\n   123\t| Orchestrator | Run setup, routing, interpretation, final gates | Claude Code orchestration agent | none | Retained interactive session |\n   124\t| Story implementor | Main story implementation | Codex `gpt-5.4 high` when Codex CLI is available | Copilot `gpt-5.4 high`, then Claude Sonnet high | Retained per-story session |\n   125\t| Story verifier | Fresh story review | Default pair: `gpt-5.4 extra high` plus Claude Sonnet high when GPT lanes are available | Claude-only verifier pair when GPT lanes are unavailable | Fresh session per verifier run |\n   126\t| Quick fixer | Small, bounded correction work | General-purpose quick-fix agent using run defaults | Any available lighter-weight lane allowed by the run | Fresh lightweight session |\n   127\t| Epic verifier | Full-epic verification | Configured epic verifier set for the run | Claude-only epic verifier set when GPT lanes are unavailable | Fresh session per verifier run |\n   128\t| Epic synthesizer | Verify and consolidate epic-level findings | Primary synthesis model for the run | Claude fallback synthesizer when GPT lanes are unavailable | Fresh one-shot session |\n   129\t\n   130\t#### CLI Operation: Initialize / Inspect Run Context\n   131\t\n   132\t| Operation | Purpose | Required Inputs | Expected Outputs | Outcome States |\n   133\t|-----------|---------|-----------------|------------------|----------------|\n   134\t| Initialize / inspect run context | Validate the spec pack and environment | epic folder path, optional explicit configuration | resolved spec-pack shape, provider availability, role defaults, detected inserts | ready, needs-user-decision, blocked |\n   135\t\n   136\t#### Implementation Log Requirements\n   137\t\n   138\tThe log must record:\n   139\t\n   140\t- active provider/model choices and verification-gate configuration\n   141\t- story sequence, dependencies, and current progress across stories\n   142\t- cumulative test progression and regression-relevant baseline information\n   143\t- enough state for the orchestrator to resume after interruption without reconstructing the run from conversation context\n   144\t\n   145\t**Relevant Tech Design Sections**\n   146\t\n   147\t- `tech-design-skill-process.md` -> Default Resolution Algorithm, Verification Gate Discovery, Flow 1, Flow 2\n   148\t- `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` -> Run Configuration Contract, Provider Availability Matrix, Flow 1: Inspect and Preflight, Verification Gate Resolution\n   149\t- `tech-design.md` -> Canonical Gate Mapping, Work Breakdown Summary\n   150\t\n   151\t*See the tech design document for full architecture, implementation targets, and test mapping.*\n   152\t\n   153\t### Definition of Done\n   154\t<!-- Jira: Definition of Done or Acceptance Criteria footer -->\n   155\t\n   156\t- Story order is resolved and recorded before implementation begins\n   157\t- Story and epic gate commands are discovered or an explicit user-decision pause is raised\n   158\t- Role defaults are resolved deterministically from available providers\n   159\t- Claude-only degraded mode is handled explicitly when no GPT lane exists\n   160\t- `team-impl-log.md` records the resolved configuration and degraded-diversity state when applicable\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
docs/spec-build/epics/01-claude-impl-cli-skill/artifacts/story-01/005-verifier-codex54-xhigh.jsonl:12:{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_4","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"nl -ba docs/spec-build/epics/01-claude-impl-cli-skill/tech-design.md | sed -n '1,260p'\"","aggregated_output":"     1\t# Technical Design: ls-claude-impl\n     2\t\n     3\t## Purpose\n     4\t\n     5\tThis design translates the `ls-claude-impl` epic into an implementable architecture for a new Claude Code orchestration skill plus a Node-compatible implementation CLI. The feature has two dense domains that need different levels of treatment: the orchestrator-facing skill surface and the CLI/runtime surface that executes bounded operations for multiple secondary harnesses. For that reason this design uses **Config B**:\n     6\t\n     7\t| Document | Purpose |\n     8\t|---|---|\n     9\t| `tech-design.md` | Decision record, context, system view, top-tier surfaces, module architecture overview, dependency and packaging decisions, work breakdown |\n    10\t| `tech-design-skill-process.md` | The orchestrator-facing skill surface: progressive disclosure docs, reading journey, state ownership, process playbook, stage transitions |\n    11\t| `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` | The CLI/runtime surface: command model, config schemas, prompt asset system, provider adapters, operation contracts, packaging |\n    12\t| `test-plan.md` | TC-to-test mapping, mock strategy, fixture strategy, test counts, chunk-level TDD plan |\n    13\t\n    14\tThe index stays small enough to be navigable while still recording the cross-cutting decisions that both companion docs inherit. The companion split follows the real boundary in this feature: one side teaches the orchestrator how the process works, the other side executes the process through a clean agent-first CLI.\n    15\t\n    16\t## Spec Validation\n    17\t\n    18\tThe epic is designable. Its major flows, ACs, and TCs describe a coherent system with clear public seams: spec-pack discovery, run configuration, prompt assembly, retained implementation sessions, fresh verification, cleanup, and epic closeout. The epic is unusually detailed for a skill feature, but the added specificity is appropriate because the feature is not just a prose skill; it is a skill plus a runtime helper plus a prompt system plus a result-contract surface.\n    19\t\n    20\tThe design does make three clarifications that should be recorded explicitly before implementation begins. None of them block design, but each one turns an implied behavior into a concrete contract the implementation can build around.\n    21\t\n    22\t| Issue | Spec Location | Resolution | Status |\n    23\t|---|---|---|---|\n    24\t| The epic requires the orchestrator to record role defaults and run choices, but it does not name a dedicated machine-readable run config file. | AC-2.4, Data Contracts, `team-impl-log.md` requirements | Introduce `impl-run.config.json` at the spec-pack root as the orchestrator-owned run configuration. `team-impl-log.md` remains the durable narrative/state record. | Resolved — clarified |\n    25\t| The epic distinguishes Codex/Copilot-backed GPT lanes from Claude-only fallback, but the harness terminology needs to preserve Claude Code as the always-present primary harness. | AC-2.2, AC-2.3, Role Model Matrix | Use `primary_harness: \"claude-code\"` plus per-role `secondary_harness: \"codex\" | \"copilot\" | \"none\"`. `none` means the role uses the primary harness only. | Resolved — clarified |\n    26\t| The epic says the CLI should be stateless across calls, but story implementation also requires retained implementor continuity. | Constraint C3, AC-4.2, AC-6.3 | Keep orchestration state outside the CLI. The CLI may emit continuation/session handles for provider sessions, but the orchestrator owns persistence, routing, and recovery through `team-impl-log.md`, `impl-run.config.json`, and any future orchestrator-managed support files. | Resolved — clarified |\n    27\t| The epic allows Copilot as the generic GPT fallback, but v1 Copilot support is limited to fresh-session roles while story implementation requires retained continuation. | AC-2.2, AC-4.2, Role Model Matrix | In v1, disallow Copilot for `story_implementor`. Retained implementor fallback order is Codex -> Claude Code primary harness. Copilot remains valid for fresh verifier, quick-fix, and synthesis roles. | Resolved — deviated |\n    28\t| The epic requires the packaged skill to include the CLI, but the current build surface only composes markdown skill outputs and bundled references. | Feature overview, CLI responsibilities implied by scope | Add a build step that bundles the modular CLI source into a single Node-compatible JS file and copies that file into the packaged skill output. | Resolved — deviated |\n    29\t\n    30\t### Tech Design Question Coverage\n    31\t\n    32\tThe epic’s Tech Design Questions are answered by this pack as follows:\n    33\t\n    34\t| Question | Primary Answer Location |\n    35\t|---|---|\n    36\t| Public CLI commands, arguments, exit codes, result formats | `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` — Command Surface, Result Contracts |\n    37\t| Prompt assets storage and assembly | `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` — Prompt Asset System |\n    38\t| Three self-review passes | `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` — Story Implementation Flow |\n    39\t| Model matrix and harness fallback | `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` — Run Config + Provider Adapters |\n    40\t| Continuation identifiers | `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` — Session Continuation Contracts |\n    41\t| Exact result fields and serialization | `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` — Result Contracts |\n    42\t| `team-impl-log.md` state model | `tech-design-skill-process.md` — Orchestrator State and Durable Artifacts |\n    43\t| How orchestrator consumes CLI results | `tech-design-skill-process.md` — Process Playbook and Stage Transitions |\n    44\t| Verification-gate hardening | `tech-design.md` — Verification Scripts; `tech-design-skill-process.md` — Initialization Flow |\n    45\t| Companion tech-design naming convention | This index — document structure and companion naming |\n    46\t| Implementor replacement vs continuation | `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` — Story Continue Rules |\n    47\t| Quick-fix narrow contract | `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` — Quick Fix Workflow |\n    48\t| Pre-epic cleanup artifacts | `tech-design-skill-process.md` and `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` — Epic Cleanup |\n    49\t| Self-review prompt evolution and stop rules | `tech-design-cli-runtime.md` — Story Implementation Flow |\n    50\t\n    51\t## Context\n    52\t\n    53\t`liminal-spec` is primarily a content-and-build repository, not a general application runtime. Most skills in the repo are markdown-first artifacts composed from `src/` and packaged into installable skill folders or standalone markdown files. That matters because `ls-claude-impl` is not a normal addition to the pack. It introduces a second kind of deliverable inside the same repo: a bundled runtime helper that must ship inside the packaged skill while still fitting the repository’s content-composition workflow.\n    54\t\n    55\tThe problem being solved is reliability of implementation orchestration, not lack of methodology. Existing implementation skill surfaces carry useful process ideas, but they rely on too much live runtime improvisation and too many layers between the orchestrator and the actual work. The new design narrows the system to three stable public surfaces. First, the skill teaches the orchestrator the process and the reading journey. Second, the orchestrator owns state and decision-making. Third, the CLI executes bounded operations and returns disciplined machine-readable results. The center of gravity shifts away from “agent teams all the way down” and toward “one orchestrator with explicit process docs and a legible execution surface.”\n    56\t\n    57\tThe future direction also matters now. The CLI is not just a local helper for this skill. It is an early public execution surface that is expected to map cleanly into a later SDK and then into web-app harness tools. That creates strong pressure toward explicit inputs, outputs, and outcome states. Hidden orchestration state inside the CLI would make later extraction harder. For the same reason, the skill should own the explanation of the process while the CLI owns execution. The orchestrator needs to understand what is happening at the process level without carrying implementation detail that belongs inside the runtime.\n    58\t\n    59\tA second pressure comes from prompt architecture. This feature does not only need CLI commands; it needs stable role prompts, reusable snippets, public insert hooks, and role-fit reading journeys. Those prompt assets are implementation-critical. They are not just docs, and they are not just helper strings. They are part of the runtime contract. The design therefore treats the prompt system as a first-class architectural surface rather than as glue hidden inside an implementation file.\n    60\t\n    61\tFinally, the repo’s existing build pipeline constrains how the feature lands. The current build emits markdown skill directories plus standalone markdown packs. It does not yet package executable runtime files into skill outputs. The design therefore includes build-system changes as part of the feature instead of leaving them to Story 0 discovery. The packaged skill must contain everything the orchestrator needs at runtime: markdown guidance plus a single bundled Node-compatible CLI file.\n    62\t\n    63\t## System View\n    64\t\n    65\tThere is no separate technical architecture document for this work. The top-tier surfaces below are therefore locally derived from the epic, nearby design notes, the existing `codex-impl` runtime, and the current repository layout.\n    66\t\n    67\t### Top-Tier Surfaces\n    68\t\n    69\t| Surface | Source | This Epic's Role |\n    70\t|---|---|---|\n    71\t| Skill Surface | Locally derived | `ls-claude-impl` markdown entrypoint and progressive-disclosure references that onboard the orchestrator and teach the process |\n    72\t| Runtime Surface | Locally derived | `ls-impl-cli` command surface, result contracts, provider adapters, prompt assembly, and packaging |\n    73\t| Build Surface | Locally derived | Manifest/build integration that composes the skill and embeds the bundled CLI artifact into packaged outputs |\n    74\t\n    75\t### System Context Diagram\n    76\t\n    77\t```mermaid\n    78\tflowchart LR\n    79\t    User[Human user] --> CC[Claude Code orchestrator]\n    80\t    CC --> Skill[ls-claude-impl SKILL.md]\n    81\t    Skill --> RefA[reading-journey.md]\n    82\t    Skill --> RefB[process-playbook.md]\n    83\t    Skill --> RefC[cli-operations.md]\n    84\t    Skill --> RefD[prompt-system.md]\n    85\t\n    86\t    CC --> SpecPack[Spec pack root]\n    87\t    SpecPack --> Epic[epic.md]\n    88\t    SpecPack --> TD[tech-design*.md]\n    89\t    SpecPack --> TP[test-plan.md]\n    90\t    SpecPack --> Stories[stories/]\n    91\t    SpecPack --> RunConfig[impl-run.config.json]\n    92\t    SpecPack --> Log[team-impl-log.md]\n    93\t\n    94\t    CC --> CLI[ls-impl-cli]\n    95\t    CLI --> PromptAssets[Embedded base prompts + snippets]\n    96\t    CLI --> Codex[Codex CLI]\n    97\t    CLI --> Copilot[Copilot CLI]\n    98\t    CLI --> Claude[Claude Code CLI]\n    99\t\n   100\t    CLI --> Results[Structured JSON results]\n   101\t    Results --> CC\n   102\t    CC --> Log\n   103\t```\n   104\t\n   105\t### External Contracts\n   106\t\n   107\tThe external contracts are narrower than the whole feature. They are the fixed points the orchestrator and CLI must agree on before implementation begins.\n   108\t\n   109\t#### Incoming Contracts\n   110\t\n   111\t| Input | Required | Source | Purpose |\n   112\t|---|---|---|---|\n   113\t| `epic.md` | yes | spec-pack root | Functional source of truth |\n   114\t| `tech-design.md` | yes | spec-pack root | Design index consumed by the orchestrator and some CLI operations |\n   115\t| `test-plan.md` | yes | spec-pack root | TC→test mapping and verification strategy |\n   116\t| `tech-design-*.md` companions | conditional | spec-pack root | Required only when the tech-design config is 4-doc |\n   117\t| `stories/` | yes | spec-pack root | Ordered story slices for implementation |\n   118\t| `impl-run.config.json` | yes | orchestrator-authored | Role/harness/model configuration for runtime operations |\n   119\t| `custom-story-impl-prompt-insert.md` | no | spec-pack root | Optional public insert for implementor prompt assembly |\n   120\t| `custom-story-verifier-prompt-insert.md` | no | spec-pack root | Optional public insert for verifier prompt assembly |\n   121\t\n   122\t#### Outgoing Contracts\n   123\t\n   124\t| Output | Producer | Destination | Purpose |\n   125\t|---|---|---|---|\n   126\t| `team-impl-log.md` updates | orchestrator | spec-pack root | Durable orchestration record and recovery state |\n   127\t| Structured command result JSON | CLI | stdout / orchestrator ingest | Machine-readable completion surface for each operation |\n   128\t| Prompt-ready execution payloads | CLI | secondary harnesses | Stable provider-facing prompt contract |\n   129\t| Bundled CLI artifact | build surface | packaged skill output | Runtime executable shipped with the skill |\n   130\t\n   131\t#### Outcome States\n   132\t\n   133\tThe CLI should use explicit outcome states instead of ambiguous free-text status messages.\n   134\t\n   135\t| Operation Class | Allowed Outcome States |\n   136\t|---|---|\n   137\t| `inspect`, `preflight` | `ready`, `needs-user-decision`, `blocked` |\n   138\t| implementation / quick-fix operations | `ready-for-verification`, `needs-followup-fix`, `needs-human-ruling`, `blocked` |\n   139\t| verifier batches | `pass`, `revise`, `block` |\n   140\t| cleanup operations | `cleaned`, `needs-more-cleanup`, `blocked` |\n   141\t| synthesis operations | `ready-for-closeout`, `needs-fixes`, `needs-more-verification`, `blocked` |\n   142\t\n   143\t#### Runtime Prerequisites\n   144\t\n   145\t| Prerequisite | Where Needed | How to Verify |\n   146\t|---|---|---|\n   147\t| Bun 1.3.x+ | local development, build, tests | `bun --version` |\n   148\t| Node-compatible runtime | packaged CLI execution | `node -v` |\n   149\t| Git repository root | CLI commands that inspect repo/worktree context | `git rev-parse --show-toplevel` |\n   150\t| `codex` CLI | only when a role uses `secondary_harness: \"codex\"` | `codex --version` plus auth/smoke command |\n   151\t| `copilot` CLI | only when a role uses `secondary_harness: \"copilot\"` | `copilot --version` plus auth/smoke command |\n   152\t| `claude` CLI | always, because primary harness is Claude Code | `claude --version` plus auth/smoke command |\n   153\t\n   154\t## Module Architecture\n   155\t\n   156\tThis feature needs changes in three repository areas: skill content, runtime process code, and build/packaging glue. The layout below keeps those responsibilities separated while making the packaged skill self-contained.\n   157\t\n   158\t```text\n   159\tsrc/\n   160\t├── phases/\n   161\t│   └── claude-impl.md                         # NEW: orchestration skill entrypoint\n   162\t├── references/\n   163\t│   ├── claude-impl-reading-journey.md         # NEW: post-setup reading journey\n   164\t│   ├── claude-impl-process-playbook.md        # NEW: full stage-by-stage process guide\n   165\t│   ├── claude-impl-cli-operations.md          # NEW: public CLI usage reference\n   166\t│   └── claude-impl-prompt-system.md           # NEW: prompt-system guide for orchestrator understanding\n   167\t└── README-pack.md / README-markdown-pack.md   # MODIFIED: new skill listed in pack docs\n   168\t\n   169\tprocesses/\n   170\t└── impl-cli/\n   171\t    ├── cli.ts                                 # NEW: citty entrypoint\n   172\t    ├── commands/\n   173\t    │   ├── inspect.ts\n   174\t    │   ├── preflight.ts\n   175\t    │   ├── story-implement.ts\n   176\t    │   ├── story-continue.ts\n   177\t    │   ├── story-verify.ts\n   178\t    │   ├── quick-fix.ts\n   179\t    │   ├── epic-cleanup.ts\n   180\t    │   ├── epic-verify.ts\n   181\t    │   └── epic-synthesize.ts\n   182\t    ├── core/\n   183\t    │   ├── config-schema.ts\n   184\t    │   ├── spec-pack.ts\n   185\t    │   ├── story-order.ts\n   186\t    │   ├── prompt-assets.ts\n   187\t    │   ├── prompt-assembly.ts\n   188\t    │   ├── provider-checks.ts\n   189\t    │   ├── provider-adapters/\n   190\t    │   │   ├── claude-code.ts\n   191\t    │   │   ├── codex.ts\n   192\t    │   │   └── copilot.ts\n   193\t    │   ├── result-contracts.ts\n   194\t    │   ├── status-codes.ts\n   195\t    │   └── embedded-assets.generated.ts\n   196\t    ├── prompts/\n   197\t    │   ├── base/\n   198\t    │   └── snippets/\n   199\t    └── tests/\n   200\t\n   201\tscripts/\n   202\t├── sync-impl-cli-assets.ts                    # NEW: embed prompt assets into generated TS\n   203\t├── build.ts                                   # MODIFIED: bundle/copy CLI artifact into packaged skill\n   204\t└── validate.ts                                # MODIFIED: validate packaged CLI artifact presence\n   205\t\n   206\tmanifest.json                                  # MODIFIED: add ls-claude-impl skill and bundled artifact metadata\n   207\t```\n   208\t\n   209\t### Module Responsibility Matrix\n   210\t\n   211\t| Module | Status | Responsibility | Dependencies | ACs Covered |\n   212\t|---|---|---|---|---|\n   213\t| `src/phases/claude-impl.md` | NEW | Initial orchestrator onboarding, setup flow, state ownership rules, progressive disclosure entrypoint | references, packaged CLI path contract | AC-1.3 to AC-1.6, AC-2.4, AC-6.1 to AC-6.3 |\n   214\t| `src/references/claude-impl-reading-journey.md` | NEW | Role-fit reading journey after spec-pack discovery | spec-pack contracts, process playbook | AC-1.5, AC-3.4 |\n   215\t| `src/references/claude-impl-process-playbook.md` | NEW | Stage-by-stage orchestration rules, receipts, escalation, progression, recovery | run config, CLI operations | AC-4 through AC-8 |\n   216\t| `src/references/claude-impl-cli-operations.md` | NEW | Public explanation of each CLI operation and outcome state | CLI command surface | AC-1.1 to AC-1.6, AC-4.1, AC-5.1, AC-8.1 to AC-8.4 |\n   217\t| `src/references/claude-impl-prompt-system.md` | NEW | Orchestrator-visible explanation of prompt primitives, inserts, and reading journeys | embedded prompt assets | AC-3.1 to AC-3.4 |\n   218\t| `processes/impl-cli/cli.ts` | NEW | Top-level citty command entrypoint and subcommand registration | command modules | AC-4.1, AC-5.1, AC-8.1 to AC-8.4 |\n   219\t| `processes/impl-cli/core/config-schema.ts` | NEW | Parse and validate `impl-run.config.json` | `c12`, `zod` | AC-2.2 to AC-2.4 |\n   220\t| `processes/impl-cli/core/spec-pack.ts` | NEW | Resolve spec-pack files, story inventory, insert files, tech-design shape | filesystem | AC-1.1 to AC-1.6 |\n   221\t| `processes/impl-cli/core/prompt-assets.ts` + `prompt-assembly.ts` | NEW | Load embedded prompt assets and assemble role prompts deterministically | generated asset module, public inserts | AC-3.1 to AC-3.4, AC-4.3 |\n   222\t| `processes/impl-cli/core/provider-checks.ts` + `provider-adapters/*` | NEW | Detect harness availability, invoke provider CLIs, resume sessions, normalize outputs | child process, provider CLIs | AC-2.1 to AC-2.4, AC-4.2, AC-5.1, AC-8.1 |\n   223\t| `processes/impl-cli/core/result-contracts.ts` | NEW | Shared result schemas and markdown/report contracts for all operations | `zod` | AC-4.5, AC-5.2, AC-7.1, AC-8.2 to AC-8.4 |\n   224\t| `scripts/sync-impl-cli-assets.ts` | NEW | Generate embedded prompt-asset module from markdown prompt sources | prompt files | AC-3.1 to AC-3.4 |\n   225\t| `scripts/build.ts` and `manifest.json` | MODIFIED | Bundle the CLI into a single Node-compatible JS file and include it in packaged skill output | Bun bundler, manifest metadata | AC-1.1, AC-3.1, packaging support for full feature |\n   226\t\n   227\t### Component Interaction Diagram\n   228\t\n   229\t```mermaid\n   230\tflowchart TD\n   231\t    O[Claude Code orchestrator]\n   232\t    S[ls-claude-impl skill files]\n   233\t    C[ls-impl-cli command]\n   234\t    SP[spec-pack resolver]\n   235\t    CFG[run config schema]\n   236\t    PA[prompt assembly]\n   237\t    AD[provider adapter]\n   238\t    PR[provider CLI runtime]\n   239\t    R[result contract]\n   240\t\n   241\t    O --> S\n   242\t    O --> C\n   243\t    C --> SP\n   244\t    C --> CFG\n   245\t    C --> PA\n   246\t    PA --> AD\n   247\t    AD --> PR\n   248\t    PR --> R\n   249\t    R --> O\n   250\t```\n   251\t\n   252\tThe key boundary is that the orchestrator uses the skill to understand what should happen, then uses the CLI to make one bounded thing happen, then writes the result into its own durable state. The CLI does not own orchestration lifecycle between calls.\n   253\t\n   254\t### Manifest and Build Metadata\n   255\t\n   256\tThe build surface needs one new manifest-level concept: a bundled runtime artifact that belongs inside the packaged skill even though it does not belong inside the composed markdown body.\n   257\t\n   258\tProposed shape:\n   259\t\n   260\t```json\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
docs/spec-build/epics/01-claude-impl-cli-skill/artifacts/story-01/005-verifier-codex54-xhigh.jsonl:15:{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_6","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"nl -ba docs/spec-build/epics/01-claude-impl-cli-skill/tech-design-skill-process.md | sed -n '1,260p'\"","aggregated_output":"     1\t# Technical Design Companion: Skill and Process Surface\n     2\t\n     3\t## Purpose\n     4\t\n     5\tThis companion covers the orchestrator-facing side of `ls-claude-impl`: the markdown skill entrypoint, the progressive-disclosure references, the orchestrator-owned state artifacts, and the process playbook that tells Claude Code what to do and when to use the CLI. The goal of this surface is not to execute work directly. Its job is to minimize cognitive load for the orchestrator while still giving the orchestrator enough understanding to supervise the implementation process critically.\n     6\t\n     7\tThe orchestrator should never have to reverse-engineer the process from CLI help text or scattered repository notes. The skill surface should answer five questions cleanly:\n     8\t\n     9\t1. What artifacts must exist before a run can begin?\n    10\t2. What should the orchestrator read first, and what can wait?\n    11\t3. What state does the orchestrator own and update?\n    12\t4. Which CLI operation should be used next?\n    13\t5. What evidence is required before the orchestrator can progress?\n    14\t\n    15\t## Skill Surface Layout\n    16\t\n    17\tThe skill should not be a monolith. It should load in layers, with each deeper file answering the question raised by the previous layer.\n    18\t\n    19\t| File | Role in the Workflow | Why It Exists |\n    20\t|---|---|---|\n    21\t| `src/phases/claude-impl.md` | Startup orientation and setup contract | Keeps initial context short and action-oriented |\n    22\t| `src/references/claude-impl-reading-journey.md` | Post-setup reading order for the spec pack | Avoids loading the full artifact world before the orchestrator knows where to look |\n    23\t| `src/references/claude-impl-process-playbook.md` | Stage-by-stage process rules | Gives the orchestrator one durable place to learn transitions, receipts, and escalation behavior |\n    24\t| `src/references/claude-impl-cli-operations.md` | Public operation guide | Keeps command semantics explicit without bloating `SKILL.md` |\n    25\t| `src/references/claude-impl-prompt-system.md` | Prompt architecture and insert explanation | Explains the runtime prompt model at the process level without exposing provider-specific implementation details inline |\n    26\t\n    27\tThe orchestrator starts with `SKILL.md`, resolves the spec-pack location, performs the minimum initial checks, and only then reads the reading-journey file. That file tells the orchestrator what to read from the spec pack and what to extract into durable state before deeper runtime work begins.\n    28\t\n    29\t### Skill-Pack Layout in Dist Output\n    30\t\n    31\tThe packaged skill should land with this shape:\n    32\t\n    33\t```text\n    34\tdist/skills/ls-claude-impl/\n    35\t├── SKILL.md\n    36\t├── references/\n    37\t│   ├── claude-impl-reading-journey.md\n    38\t│   ├── claude-impl-process-playbook.md\n    39\t│   ├── claude-impl-cli-operations.md\n    40\t│   └── claude-impl-prompt-system.md\n    41\t└── bin/\n    42\t    └── ls-impl-cli.cjs\n    43\t```\n    44\t\n    45\tThe runtime file lives beside the docs, but the docs remain the authoritative explanation of the process. The orchestrator should be able to succeed by reading the docs and then using the CLI. The CLI should not have to teach the methodology.\n    46\t\n    47\t## Orchestrator-Owned Artifacts\n    48\t\n    49\tThe orchestrator is the state authority for a run. The CLI is not the owner of run lifecycle, progression, or recovery. That boundary is what keeps the future SDK/harness surface clean.\n    50\t\n    51\t### `impl-run.config.json`\n    52\t\n    53\t`impl-run.config.json` is the machine-readable declaration of the intended run shape. The orchestrator authors it or updates it during initialization. The CLI validates it before any provider-backed work begins.\n    54\t\n    55\t```json\n    56\t{\n    57\t  \"version\": 1,\n    58\t  \"primary_harness\": \"claude-code\",\n    59\t  \"story_implementor\": {\n    60\t    \"secondary_harness\": \"codex\",\n    61\t    \"model\": \"gpt-5.4\",\n    62\t    \"reasoning_effort\": \"high\"\n    63\t  },\n    64\t  \"quick_fixer\": {\n    65\t    \"secondary_harness\": \"codex\",\n    66\t    \"model\": \"gpt-5.4\",\n    67\t    \"reasoning_effort\": \"medium\"\n    68\t  },\n    69\t  \"story_verifier_1\": {\n    70\t    \"secondary_harness\": \"codex\",\n    71\t    \"model\": \"gpt-5.4\",\n    72\t    \"reasoning_effort\": \"xhigh\"\n    73\t  },\n    74\t  \"story_verifier_2\": {\n    75\t    \"secondary_harness\": \"none\",\n    76\t    \"model\": \"claude-sonnet\",\n    77\t    \"reasoning_effort\": \"high\"\n    78\t  },\n    79\t  \"self_review\": {\n    80\t    \"passes\": 3\n    81\t  },\n    82\t  \"epic_verifiers\": [\n    83\t    {\n    84\t      \"label\": \"epic-verifier-1\",\n    85\t      \"secondary_harness\": \"codex\",\n    86\t      \"model\": \"gpt-5.4\",\n    87\t      \"reasoning_effort\": \"xhigh\"\n    88\t    },\n    89\t    {\n    90\t      \"label\": \"epic-verifier-2\",\n    91\t      \"secondary_harness\": \"none\",\n    92\t      \"model\": \"claude-sonnet\",\n    93\t      \"reasoning_effort\": \"high\"\n    94\t    }\n    95\t  ],\n    96\t  \"epic_synthesizer\": {\n    97\t    \"secondary_harness\": \"codex\",\n    98\t    \"model\": \"gpt-5.4\",\n    99\t    \"reasoning_effort\": \"xhigh\"\n   100\t  }\n   101\t}\n   102\t```\n   103\t\n   104\tThe key simplicity rule is that the file should only say what the orchestrator actually needs to decide: the primary harness, the per-role secondary harness, the model selection, and the self-review pass count. It should not carry derived values, convenience aliases, or runtime details that the orchestrator does not need to reason about.\n   105\t\n   106\t### Default Resolution Algorithm\n   107\t\n   108\tThe orchestrator owns the config file, but it should not invent defaults ad hoc. The skill surface should teach one deterministic default-generation algorithm:\n   109\t\n   110\t1. Set `primary_harness` to `claude-code`.\n   111\t2. Probe secondary harness availability in this order:\n   112\t   - Codex available\n   113\t   - else Copilot available\n   114\t   - else no secondary harness\n   115\t3. If Codex is available, use Codex as the default secondary harness for all GPT-lane roles:\n   116\t   - story implementor: `codex`, `gpt-5.4`, `high`\n   117\t   - quick fixer: `codex`, `gpt-5.4`, `medium`\n   118\t   - story verifier 1: `codex`, `gpt-5.4`, `xhigh`\n   119\t   - story verifier 2: `none`, `claude-sonnet`, `high`\n   120\t   - epic verifier 1: `codex`, `gpt-5.4`, `xhigh`\n   121\t   - epic verifier 2: `none`, `claude-sonnet`, `high`\n   122\t   - epic synthesizer: `codex`, `gpt-5.4`, `xhigh`\n   123\t4. If Codex is unavailable but Copilot is available, use Copilot only for fresh-session roles:\n   124\t   - story implementor: `none`, `claude-sonnet`, `high`\n   125\t   - quick fixer: `copilot`, `gpt-5.4`, `medium`\n   126\t   - story verifier 1: `copilot`, `gpt-5.4`, `xhigh`\n   127\t   - story verifier 2: `none`, `claude-sonnet`, `high`\n   128\t   - epic verifier 1: `copilot`, `gpt-5.4`, `xhigh`\n   129\t   - epic verifier 2: `none`, `claude-sonnet`, `high`\n   130\t   - epic synthesizer: `copilot`, `gpt-5.4`, `xhigh`\n   131\t   Story implementor still falls back to `secondary_harness: \"none\"` because v1 retained implementor continuation is not defined for Copilot.\n   132\t5. If no GPT secondary harness is available, switch all roles to `secondary_harness: \"none\"` and record a degraded-diversity condition in `team-impl-log.md`.\n   133\t\n   134\tThis keeps config authorship with the orchestrator while still satisfying the epic’s requirement that defaults and fallback behavior be resolved deterministically before implementation begins.\n   135\t\n   136\t### `team-impl-log.md`\n   137\t\n   138\t`team-impl-log.md` is the durable orchestration record. It is the primary run-state artifact, not a narrative afterthought. The orchestrator updates it after setup, after each command result, at every story transition, and before epic closeout.\n   139\t\n   140\tRequired sections:\n   141\t\n   142\t| Section | Purpose |\n   143\t|---|---|\n   144\t| Run Overview | spec-pack root, current status, current story, current phase |\n   145\t| Run Configuration | snapshot of the validated `impl-run.config.json` choices |\n   146\t| Verification Gates | story and epic gate commands discovered from project policy |\n   147\t| Story Sequence | full story list and current position |\n   148\t| Receipts | pre-acceptance evidence and dispositions by story |\n   149\t| Cumulative Baselines | test-count expectations and regression checks |\n   150\t| Cleanup / Epic Verification | deferred items, cleanup status, final verification state |\n   151\t| Open Risks / Accepted Risks | explicit unresolved or accepted-risk items |\n   152\t\n   153\tThe log remains markdown because it is both human-facing and agent-facing. The orchestrator needs to read and update it directly. A second support file can be added later if highly structured state becomes necessary, but the v1 feature should keep the required surface small.\n   154\t\n   155\t### State Enum\n   156\t\n   157\tThe log should carry one explicit current-state field using this enum:\n   158\t\n   159\t| State | Meaning |\n   160\t|---|---|\n   161\t| `SETUP` | skill loaded, spec-pack root being resolved, config/log initialization not complete |\n   162\t| `BETWEEN_STORIES` | ready to start the next story |\n   163\t| `STORY_ACTIVE` | implementation / verification / fix routing in progress for one story |\n   164\t| `PRE_EPIC_VERIFY` | all stories accepted, cleanup and epic closeout not yet complete |\n   165\t| `EPIC_VERIFY_ACTIVE` | cleanup, epic verifier batch, or synthesis is in progress |\n   166\t| `COMPLETE` | run complete |\n   167\t| `FAILED` | blocked or failed terminally pending human decision |\n   168\t\n   169\t### `team-impl-log.md` Template\n   170\t\n   171\tThe exact text can evolve, but the heading contract should be fixed.\n   172\t\n   173\t```markdown\n   174\t# Team Implementation Log\n   175\t\n   176\t## Run Overview\n   177\t- State: BETWEEN_STORIES\n   178\t- Spec Pack Root: /abs/path\n   179\t- Current Story: story-03\n   180\t- Current Phase: story-verify\n   181\t\n   182\t## Run Configuration\n   183\t- Primary Harness: claude-code\n   184\t- Story Implementor: codex / gpt-5.4 / high\n   185\t- Quick Fixer: codex / gpt-5.4 / medium\n   186\t- Story Verifier 1: codex / gpt-5.4 / xhigh\n   187\t- Story Verifier 2: none / claude-sonnet / high\n   188\t- Self Review Passes: 3\n   189\t- Degraded Diversity: false\n   190\t\n   191\t## Verification Gates\n   192\t- Story Gate: bun run green-verify\n   193\t- Epic Gate: bun run verify-all\n   194\t- Gate Discovery Source: package.json scripts\n   195\t\n   196\t## Story Sequence\n   197\t- story-00-foundation\n   198\t- story-01-run-setup\n   199\t- story-02-prompt-composition\n   200\t\n   201\t## Current Continuation Handles\n   202\t- Story Implementor:\n   203\t  - Story: story-03\n   204\t  - Provider: codex\n   205\t  - Session ID: abc123\n   206\t\n   207\t## Story Receipts\n   208\t### story-02\n   209\t- Implementor Evidence Ref: artifacts/story-02/implement-result.json\n   210\t- Verifier Evidence Refs:\n   211\t  - artifacts/story-02/verify-primary.json\n   212\t  - artifacts/story-02/verify-secondary.json\n   213\t- Gate Result: pass\n   214\t- Dispositions:\n   215\t  - FIX-1: fixed\n   216\t  - RISK-2: accepted-risk\n   217\t- Open Risks:\n   218\t  - none\n   219\t\n   220\t## Cumulative Baselines\n   221\t- Baseline Before Current Story: 48\n   222\t- Expected After Current Story: 56\n   223\t- Latest Actual Total: 56\n   224\t\n   225\t## Cleanup / Epic Verification\n   226\t- Cleanup Artifact: artifacts/cleanup/cleanup-batch.md\n   227\t- Cleanup Status: not-started\n   228\t- Epic Verification Status: not-started\n   229\t\n   230\t## Open Risks / Accepted Risks\n   231\t- none\n   232\t```\n   233\t\n   234\tThe orchestrator can add prose beneath these headings, but these sections and labels should be present so recovery is deterministic.\n   235\t\n   236\t### Story Receipt Contract\n   237\t\n   238\tEach accepted story should record:\n   239\t\n   240\t- story id and title\n   241\t- implementor result path\n   242\t- verifier result paths\n   243\t- final story gate command + pass/fail outcome\n   244\t- dispositions for each unresolved finding (`fixed`, `accepted-risk`, `defer`)\n   245\t- cumulative test baseline before and after the story\n   246\t- any active continuation handles that remain relevant\n   247\t\n   248\t## Verification Gate Discovery\n   249\t\n   250\tGate discovery must follow a fixed precedence order so the orchestrator does not improvise.\n   251\t\n   252\t1. Explicit CLI flags supplied for the current run\n   253\t2. Explicit entries in `impl-run.config.json` if later added\n   254\t3. package scripts in the repo root\n   255\t4. repository policy docs (`AGENTS.md`, `README`, related process docs)\n   256\t5. CI configuration as supporting evidence\n   257\t6. if still ambiguous: pause with `needs-user-decision`\n   258\t\n   259\tThe playbook should teach the orchestrator to record:\n   260\t\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
docs/spec-build/epics/01-claude-impl-cli-skill/artifacts/story-01/005-verifier-codex54-xhigh.jsonl:16:{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_7","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"nl -ba docs/spec-build/epics/01-claude-impl-cli-skill/tech-design-cli-runtime.md | sed -n '1,260p'\"","aggregated_output":"     1\t# Technical Design Companion: CLI Runtime Surface\n     2\t\n     3\t## Purpose\n     4\t\n     5\tThis companion covers the `ls-impl-cli` runtime that executes bounded operations on behalf of the `ls-claude-impl` orchestrator. The CLI is not the methodology. It is the execution surface that makes the methodology practical. It validates readiness, assembles provider-facing prompts, calls secondary harnesses when configured, captures structured outputs, and returns disciplined result contracts to the orchestrator.\n     6\t\n     7\tThe design goal is an agent-first CLI. Every command should correspond to a clear process action that the orchestrator already understands from the skill docs. The CLI should hide internal complexity but not produce mystery. It should accept explicit inputs, return explicit results, and avoid holding orchestration lifecycle in hidden runtime state between calls.\n     8\t\n     9\t## Runtime Surface Overview\n    10\t\n    11\tThe runtime has five responsibilities:\n    12\t\n    13\t1. Resolve and validate the spec-pack surface.\n    14\t2. Load and validate the orchestrator-owned run config.\n    15\t3. Assemble prompts from embedded base prompts, snippets, runtime values, and public inserts.\n    16\t4. Execute one bounded operation through the appropriate primary/secondary harness combination.\n    17\t5. Return structured results that the orchestrator can persist and act on.\n    18\t\n    19\tThe runtime does **not** own:\n    20\t\n    21\t- story progression\n    22\t- acceptance decisions\n    23\t- cumulative baselines across the whole run\n    24\t- cleanup review decisions\n    25\t- epic closeout decisions\n    26\t\n    27\tThose remain with the orchestrator.\n    28\t\n    29\t## Shared Result Envelope\n    30\t\n    31\tEvery command should return the same outer JSON envelope so the orchestrator can ingest results without command-specific parsing rules.\n    32\t\n    33\t```typescript\n    34\texport interface CliError {\n    35\t  code: string;\n    36\t  message: string;\n    37\t  detail?: string;\n    38\t}\n    39\t\n    40\texport interface CliArtifactRef {\n    41\t  kind: string;\n    42\t  path: string;\n    43\t}\n    44\t\n    45\texport interface CliResultEnvelope<T> {\n    46\t  command: string;\n    47\t  version: 1;\n    48\t  status: \"ok\" | \"needs-user-decision\" | \"blocked\" | \"error\";\n    49\t  outcome: string;\n    50\t  result?: T;\n    51\t  errors: CliError[];\n    52\t  warnings: string[];\n    53\t  artifacts: CliArtifactRef[];\n    54\t  startedAt: string;\n    55\t  finishedAt: string;\n    56\t}\n    57\t```\n    58\t\n    59\tThe JSON envelope is the source of truth. Human-readable `stderr` is allowed for progress or debugging, but the orchestrator should route decisions from the envelope rather than from ad hoc terminal text.\n    60\t\n    61\tSuggested stable error codes:\n    62\t\n    63\t- `INVALID_SPEC_PACK`\n    64\t- `INVALID_RUN_CONFIG`\n    65\t- `VERIFICATION_GATE_UNRESOLVED`\n    66\t- `PROVIDER_UNAVAILABLE`\n    67\t- `PROVIDER_OUTPUT_INVALID`\n    68\t- `CONTINUATION_HANDLE_INVALID`\n    69\t- `PROMPT_ASSET_MISSING`\n    70\t- `PROMPT_INSERT_INVALID`\n    71\t\n    72\t## Public CLI Contract\n    73\t\n    74\tThe public CLI contract consists of:\n    75\t\n    76\t1. command signatures in `Command Signatures`\n    77\t2. shared JSON envelope in `Shared Result Envelope`\n    78\t3. stdout/stderr/artifact behavior in `Public CLI IO Contract`\n    79\t4. exit-code and routing behavior in `Exit Codes` and `Result Routing Matrix`\n    80\t5. provider execution assumptions in `Provider Invocation Contracts`\n    81\t\n    82\tAn implementation that matches those five surfaces should be interchangeable at the orchestrator boundary even if internal module structure changes later.\n    83\t\n    84\t## Command Surface\n    85\t\n    86\tThe public CLI surface should be small and stable.\n    87\t\n    88\t| Command | Purpose | Required Inputs | Primary Outputs | Outcome States |\n    89\t|---|---|---|---|---|\n    90\t| `inspect` | Resolve spec-pack layout and story inventory | spec-pack root | spec-pack summary, story order, insert presence | `ready`, `needs-user-decision`, `blocked` |\n    91\t| `preflight` | Validate run config, provider availability, prompt assets, and run readiness | spec-pack root, `impl-run.config.json` | readiness report, validated config, provider matrix | `ready`, `needs-user-decision`, `blocked` |\n    92\t| `story-implement` | Start implementation for one story | story id, spec-pack root, run config | implementor result, continuation handle | `ready-for-verification`, `needs-followup-fix`, `needs-human-ruling`, `blocked` |\n    93\t| `story-continue` | Continue a retained implementor session for the current story | continuation handle, follow-up request | continued implementor result | `ready-for-verification`, `needs-followup-fix`, `needs-human-ruling`, `blocked` |\n    94\t| `story-verify` | Run a fresh verifier batch for one story | story id, run config, verification context | verifier batch result array | `pass`, `revise`, `block` |\n    95\t| `quick-fix` | Apply a narrow, bounded fix request | fix request, affected scope, role config | quick-fix result | `ready-for-verification`, `needs-more-routing`, `blocked` |\n    96\t| `epic-cleanup` | Apply cleanup-only corrections before epic verification | cleanup batch, selected fix workflow | cleanup result | `cleaned`, `needs-more-cleanup`, `blocked` |\n    97\t| `epic-verify` | Run fresh epic-level verification | spec-pack root, run config | epic verifier result array | `pass`, `revise`, `block` |\n    98\t| `epic-synthesize` | Verify and consolidate epic-level findings | epic verifier results, run config | synthesis result | `ready-for-closeout`, `needs-fixes`, `needs-more-verification`, `blocked` |\n    99\t\n   100\tThe CLI with no arguments should print quick-start help only. The full process explanation stays in the skill docs.\n   101\t\n   102\t### Command Signatures\n   103\t\n   104\tThe public signatures should stay stable even if internal implementation changes.\n   105\t\n   106\t| Command | Signature |\n   107\t|---|---|\n   108\t| `inspect` | `ls-impl-cli inspect --spec-pack-root <path> [--json]` |\n   109\t| `preflight` | `ls-impl-cli preflight --spec-pack-root <path> [--config <path>] [--story-gate <cmd>] [--epic-gate <cmd>] [--json]` |\n   110\t| `story-implement` | `ls-impl-cli story-implement --spec-pack-root <path> --story-id <id> [--config <path>] [--json]` |\n   111\t| `story-continue` | `ls-impl-cli story-continue --spec-pack-root <path> --story-id <id> --provider <provider> --session-id <id> [--config <path>] [--followup-file <path> | --followup-text <text>] [--json]` |\n   112\t| `story-verify` | `ls-impl-cli story-verify --spec-pack-root <path> --story-id <id> [--config <path>] [--json]` |\n   113\t| `quick-fix` | `ls-impl-cli quick-fix --spec-pack-root <path> --story-id <id> --request-file <path> [--scope-file <path>] [--config <path>] [--json]` |\n   114\t| `epic-cleanup` | `ls-impl-cli epic-cleanup --spec-pack-root <path> --cleanup-batch <path> [--config <path>] [--json]` |\n   115\t| `epic-verify` | `ls-impl-cli epic-verify --spec-pack-root <path> [--config <path>] [--json]` |\n   116\t| `epic-synthesize` | `ls-impl-cli epic-synthesize --spec-pack-root <path> --verifier-report <path> --verifier-report <path> [--config <path>] [--json]` |\n   117\t\n   118\tAll commands should support `--json` for machine-readable output. Human-readable summaries may exist for manual use, but the orchestrator contract should be the JSON payload.\n   119\t\n   120\t### Public CLI IO Contract\n   121\t\n   122\tThe CLI should behave consistently across commands.\n   123\t\n   124\t| Surface | Rule |\n   125\t|---|---|\n   126\t| stdout with `--json` | emit exactly one `CliResultEnvelope<T>` JSON object |\n   127\t| stdout without `--json` | emit a concise human-readable summary only |\n   128\t| stderr | reserved for progress/debugging; never required for orchestration routing |\n   129\t| persisted artifacts | write the same JSON envelope that was emitted on stdout |\n   130\t| default config path | `<spec-pack-root>/impl-run.config.json` unless `--config` overrides it |\n   131\t| default artifact root | `<spec-pack-root>/artifacts/` |\n   132\t\n   133\t### Command Examples\n   134\t\n   135\t```bash\n   136\tnode bin/ls-impl-cli.cjs inspect --spec-pack-root /abs/spec-pack --json\n   137\tnode bin/ls-impl-cli.cjs preflight --spec-pack-root /abs/spec-pack --json\n   138\tnode bin/ls-impl-cli.cjs story-implement --spec-pack-root /abs/spec-pack --story-id story-03 --json\n   139\tnode bin/ls-impl-cli.cjs story-verify --spec-pack-root /abs/spec-pack --story-id story-03 --json\n   140\tnode bin/ls-impl-cli.cjs epic-cleanup --spec-pack-root /abs/spec-pack --cleanup-batch /abs/spec-pack/artifacts/cleanup/cleanup-batch.md --json\n   141\t```\n   142\t\n   143\tFor commands whose inner payload also contains an `outcome`, the envelope `outcome` is the routing source of truth and must match the inner payload exactly. Schema validation should reject mismatches.\n   144\t\n   145\t### Exit Codes\n   146\t\n   147\tExit codes are a coarse routing signal. The JSON payload remains the source of truth.\n   148\t\n   149\t| Exit Code | Meaning |\n   150\t|---|---|\n   151\t| `0` | Command completed and produced a non-blocking outcome (`ready`, `ready-for-verification`, `pass`, `cleaned`, `ready-for-closeout`) |\n   152\t| `2` | Command completed but requires follow-up (`needs-user-decision`, `needs-followup-fix`, `needs-human-ruling`, `revise`, `needs-more-routing`, `needs-more-cleanup`, `needs-fixes`, `needs-more-verification`) |\n   153\t| `3` | Command is blocked by environment, spec-pack, config, or provider readiness issue |\n   154\t| `1` | Invalid invocation, schema parse failure, or uncaught runtime error |\n   155\t\n   156\t### Result Routing Matrix\n   157\t\n   158\tThis matrix is authoritative for handler implementation and tests.\n   159\t\n   160\t| Command Outcome | Envelope Status | Exit Code | Orchestrator Action |\n   161\t|---|---|---:|---|\n   162\t| `ready` | `ok` | 0 | proceed to next setup step |\n   163\t| `ready-for-verification` | `ok` | 0 | run verification or next bounded step |\n   164\t| `pass` | `ok` | 0 | evaluate for acceptance or next stage |\n   165\t| `cleaned` | `ok` | 0 | move into epic verification |\n   166\t| `ready-for-closeout` | `ok` | 0 | run final orchestrator-owned gate |\n   167\t| `needs-user-decision` | `needs-user-decision` | 2 | pause and request human clarification |\n   168\t| `needs-followup-fix` | `ok` | 2 | route same-session follow-up or fix path |\n   169\t| `needs-human-ruling` | `needs-user-decision` | 2 | pause for orchestrator/human ruling |\n   170\t| `revise` | `ok` | 2 | route fix and rerun verification |\n   171\t| `needs-more-routing` | `ok` | 2 | select another bounded correction path |\n   172\t| `needs-more-cleanup` | `ok` | 2 | continue cleanup cycle |\n   173\t| `needs-fixes` | `ok` | 2 | route fixes before closeout |\n   174\t| `needs-more-verification` | `ok` | 2 | launch additional verification/synthesis |\n   175\t| `blocked` | `blocked` | 3 | stop and inspect blocking error details |\n   176\t| parse/schema/runtime failure | `error` | 1 | treat as CLI failure rather than feature-state outcome |\n   177\t\n   178\t## Runtime Module Layout\n   179\t\n   180\t```text\n   181\tprocesses/impl-cli/\n   182\t├── cli.ts\n   183\t├── commands/\n   184\t│   ├── inspect.ts\n   185\t│   ├── preflight.ts\n   186\t│   ├── story-implement.ts\n   187\t│   ├── story-continue.ts\n   188\t│   ├── story-verify.ts\n   189\t│   ├── quick-fix.ts\n   190\t│   ├── epic-cleanup.ts\n   191\t│   ├── epic-verify.ts\n   192\t│   └── epic-synthesize.ts\n   193\t├── core/\n   194\t│   ├── config-schema.ts\n   195\t│   ├── spec-pack.ts\n   196\t│   ├── story-order.ts\n   197\t│   ├── prompt-assets.ts\n   198\t│   ├── prompt-assembly.ts\n   199\t│   ├── provider-checks.ts\n   200\t│   ├── provider-adapters/\n   201\t│   │   ├── claude-code.ts\n   202\t│   │   ├── codex.ts\n   203\t│   │   └── copilot.ts\n   204\t│   ├── result-contracts.ts\n   205\t│   ├── status-codes.ts\n   206\t│   ├── command-context.ts\n   207\t│   └── embedded-assets.generated.ts\n   208\t└── prompts/\n   209\t    ├── base/\n   210\t    └── snippets/\n   211\t```\n   212\t\n   213\tThe command modules stay thin. They parse command-specific flags with `citty`, call into core services, and print structured JSON. All real behavior lives in `core/`.\n   214\t\n   215\t### Core Service Interfaces\n   216\t\n   217\tThe command handlers should depend on a small set of explicit core interfaces.\n   218\t\n   219\t```typescript\n   220\texport interface SpecPackResolver {\n   221\t  resolve(specPackRoot: string): Promise<InspectResult>;\n   222\t}\n   223\t\n   224\texport interface VerificationGateResolver {\n   225\t  resolve(input: {\n   226\t    specPackRoot: string;\n   227\t    explicitStoryGate?: string;\n   228\t    explicitEpicGate?: string;\n   229\t  }): Promise<VerificationGateConfig | CliError>;\n   230\t}\n   231\t\n   232\texport interface ArtifactWriter {\n   233\t  write<T>(params: {\n   234\t    specPackRoot: string;\n   235\t    command: string;\n   236\t    storyId?: string;\n   237\t    payload: CliResultEnvelope<T>;\n   238\t  }): Promise<CliArtifactRef>;\n   239\t}\n   240\t\n   241\texport interface ProviderResultParser<T> {\n   242\t  parse(raw: ProviderExecutionResult): Promise<T | CliError>;\n   243\t}\n   244\t```\n   245\t\n   246\tThese interfaces are deliberately smaller than the whole runtime. They pin the boundaries that are most likely to drift during implementation.\n   247\t\n   248\t## Run Configuration Contract\n   249\t\n   250\tThe CLI consumes an explicit orchestrator-owned JSON file. The contract is intentionally lean.\n   251\t\n   252\t```typescript\n   253\texport type PrimaryHarness = \"claude-code\";\n   254\texport type SecondaryHarness = \"codex\" | \"copilot\" | \"none\";\n   255\texport type ReasoningEffort = \"low\" | \"medium\" | \"high\" | \"xhigh\";\n   256\t\n   257\texport interface RoleAssignment {\n   258\t  secondary_harness: SecondaryHarness;\n   259\t  model: string;\n   260\t  reasoning_effort: ReasoningEffort;\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
docs/spec-build/epics/01-claude-impl-cli-skill/artifacts/story-01/005-verifier-codex54-xhigh.jsonl:18:{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_8","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"nl -ba docs/spec-build/epics/01-claude-impl-cli-skill/test-plan.md | sed -n '1,300p'\"","aggregated_output":"     1\t# Test Plan: ls-claude-impl\n     2\t\n     3\t## Purpose\n     4\t\n     5\tThis plan maps every TC from the `ls-claude-impl` epic to a concrete test surface. The feature spans both content and runtime, so the test plan does too. Some requirements are verified through packaged skill-content tests because the skill is the source of process truth. Others are verified through CLI command-entrypoint tests because the CLI is the execution surface. Together they cover the full chain:\n     6\t\n     7\t```text\n     8\tEpic AC -> TC -> skill/runtime test -> implementation\n     9\t```\n    10\t\n    11\tThe main testing principle is the same one used elsewhere in the methodology: test at public seams. For this feature the public seams are:\n    12\t\n    13\t- packaged skill files\n    14\t- CLI command entrypoints\n    15\t- provider adapter boundaries\n    16\t- bundled runtime artifact\n    17\t\n    18\tSome requirements in this feature are intentionally **process-contract only** rather than runtime-enforced. Those are validated through skill-content and CLI-guide tests because the orchestrator, not the CLI, owns that behavior. Wherever a requirement is covered that way, the coverage note should be read as “documentation/process contract,” not “hard runtime enforcement.”\n    19\t\n    20\t## Testing Strategy\n    21\t\n    22\t### Test Pyramid for This Feature\n    23\t\n    24\t```text\n    25\t         /\\\n    26\t        /  \\  Manual verification\n    27\t       /----\\  - load skill, follow setup, run packaged CLI on fixture spec pack\n    28\t      /      \\\n    29\t     /--------\\  Command-entrypoint tests\n    30\t    /          \\  - inspect